{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_bullock_ver01/data/sn82016181/00516999615/1937112201/0685.xml":{"full_text":"Senate Gets Farm Bill\nbut Wages Measure\nIs Still Jammed\nBy United Press\nThe Administration\u2019s far-reaching farm bill, provid\ning for stabilization of farm income and checks against\ncrop scarcities, was reported favorably to the Senate\ntoday by the Agriulture Committee.\nThe report, unanimously agreed\nupon by the committee after a week\nend session. will permit the Senate\nto begin deliberations tomorrow. Ma\njority Leader Alben W. Barkley (D.\nKy said he hoped to obtain final\naction on the bill by the week-end.\nESTIMATES DIFFER\nHe estimated that the farm pro\ngram will cost a little less than the\n$500 000,000 in soil conservation funds\nand approximately $125,000,000 from\ncustoms receipts already available.\nOther estimates, including those of\nthe Agriculture Department, have\nplaced the cost as high as $700,000,000\nMeanwhile. House Majority Leader\n8am Rayburn iD Tex.) said after\na conference with Chairman Marvin\nJones iD. Tex of the House Agri\nculture Committee that the House\nshould be able to begin debate on\nits new farm bill Wednesday, or Fri\nday. after the Thanksgiving recess.\nWAGES BILL SHOWDOWN\nIn the House, an indication will\nbe given tomorrow as to the fate\nof\nthe\nsecond important special\nsession legislation the wages and\nhours bill Outlook for the labor\nstandards measure was not bright but\nAdministration leaders were ready to\nattempt to blast it out of a Rules\nCommittee deadlock if Chairman\nJohn J. O'Connor (D, NY.) cannot\npromise action tomorrow.\nCongressional leaders believed tech\nnical obstacles and their promises of\ntax revision in January had ended the\nrebel campaign for action at the\nspecial session to revise or repeal the\nundistributed profits tax.\nFILIBUSTERING AN OBSTACLE\nStrong opposition to the wages\nhours bill and the Government reor\nganization bill appeared likely to\nprevent their enactment at the spec\nLeaders believed there\nlai session.\nwas a better chance for the national\nplanning measure setting up modi\nfied \"little TVA\" regions.\nFilibustering appeared to be as\ngreat an obstacle to the general pro\ngram\u2014excepting the farm bill\u2014as the\ninsurgent demands that Congress\ndrop the President's program to act\nat once for the encouragement of\nbusiness.\nSOUTHERN SENATORS ADAMANT\nSenate filibustering was scheduled\nto continue this afternoon against\nthe anti-lynching bill. The obstruc\ntionists were assured of success as\nthe farm bill will displace the meas\nThe Senate has\nlire tomorrow.\nagreed to take up the anti-lynching\nbill again immediately after action\non the crop control measure, but the\nprospects of a vote are dim.\nSen.\nJosiah Bailey (D, N C Sen. Tom\nConnally (D., Tex), Sen. Ellison D.\nSmith (D., S. C), Sen. James F.\nByrnes (D., S. C.), and others were\nunderstood to have organized at least\n15 senators to filibuster the measure\nwhenever it comes up.\nBORAH WANTS CONFIDENCE\nSen. William E. Borah (R. Ida),\ndeclared that there was more to the\nproblem of business aid than mere\ntax revision. \"The undivided-profits\ntax is only one item in this business\nrecession,\u201d he said. The law should\nbe modified but not repealed.\n\"There is a definite uneasiness, a\nlack of confidence in business.\nP\nFEATURES OF FARM BILL\nAPPROVED BY SENATORS\nThe Senate farm bill would pro\nvide for control of wheat, field corn,\ncotton, tobacco and rice, for a three\nyear period beginning in 1938.\nThe Senate committee made a\n\u201cblanket\u201d authorization for finances.\nThe Agriculture Secretary would de\ntermine the cost, estimated at ap\nproximately $700,000,000, and his\nrecommendation subsequently would\nbe considered by the Budget Bu\nreal and Congress.\nThe\ncommittee\nwrote\nthe\n\u201cblanket\u201d authorization into the\nbill despite warnings from Roose\nvelt that funds required in addition\nto the $500,000,000 available under\nthe soil conservation program must\nbe obtained from new sources.\nIt the President and Congress would\ndemonstrate their determination to\ncurtail expenditures rather than in\ncreasing taxes, this would go far\ntoward encouraging business and re\nstoring confidence.\u201d\nBorah also said he felt that an\n\"unequivocal\" pronouncement that\nthe United States will not be in\nvolved in the China war also was es\nsential to reduction of business fears.\nVisitors Searched\nat Ted Creech Trial\nThe trial of Ted Creech, burly Har\nlan County mine superintendent, got\nunder way today as U. S. Deputy\nMarshal searched all visitors to the\ncourt room for concealed weapons.\nCreech is being tried on charges of\nperjury before the U. S. Senate Civil\nLiberties Committee in April during\nthe investigation of the activities of\ncoal mine owners in \u201cBloody Harlan\nCounty.\"\nCreech was arrested after he denied\nbefore the Congressional hearing that\nhe had threatened Richard C. Tack\nett. a witness. Tackett, a Kentucky\nminer and former deputy sheriff, told\nauthorities that he was approached\nby Creech in the hallway during a\nrecess from the hearing.\nBefore court opened this morning\nsome 25 persons, waiting to get in\nwere surprised at the compulsory\nsearch. Some refused to be \u201cfrisked\"\nand went away instead. no guns were\nfound.\nGertrude Evans Dies\nGertrude Evans, 22. Central grad\nuate and active member of the Na\ntional Womans Party, the Women\u2019s\nTrade Union League and the Pierce\nHall Players while she was employed\nbv the Federal Trade Commission\nhere, died Saturday at Tampa where\nshe recently obtained a new position.\nfriends here learned today.\nShe is\nsurvived by her parents, a sister and\ntwo brothers.\nSHappy Birthdays\nSDoriss\nI\nSOMERVILLE, N. J., Nov. 22\u2014Doris\nDuke Cromwell came into the second\nthird of her *30,000,000 inheritance\ntoday her 25th birthday and\nclinched the title of \"the richest girl\nin the world.\u201d The birthday present,\nmade passible by the trust fund set\nup for her by her father, the late\nJames Buchanan Duke, was estimated\nto be worth from *10,000,000 to $18,\n000.000. The tobacco heiress and her\nhusband, James H. Cromwell, planned\nno celebration save a quiet family\ngathering.\nAuto Strike\n(Continued From Page 1)\nber Co. today after members of the\nUnited Rubber Workers voted to ac\ncept a tentative settlement effected\nby the National Labor Relations\nBoard ending a sit-down strike which\nbegan Thursday.\nUnion officials announced they\nwould file charges today with the\nLabor Board against Gov. Martin L.\nDavey who had called out 2000 Na\ntional Guardsmen to give protection\nto all Goodyear workers who wished\nto return to work. Strikers filed from\nthe plant Saturday after hearing that\nguardsmen were mobilizing.\nDetails of the agreement were not\nmade public. It was understood to\nprovide: (1) Gradual return to work\nof 1600 discharged men, to be based\nupon the degree of business pickup.\nTheir discharge had caused the strike;\n(2) distribution of work thruout plant\nunits on a proportionate basis, elim\ninating concentration of layoffs in\nany given group; (3) recognition of\nworkers\u2019 seniority in possible future\nlayoffs, and (4) guarantee that men\nof 10 years\u2019 service would not be dis\ncharged.\nThe strike was based specifically on\nthe claim that the discharges were\nordered in the tire building division\nand not distributed thruout the\nplants. It was charged that by this\nprocess, tire builders with 10 or more\nyears\u2019 service had been discharged\nwhile workers of less seniority in\nother units were retained.\nThe union membership voted to\nratify the agreement after more than\nfive hours\u2019 debate. James P. Miller,\nregional N. L. R. B. director, was the\nlink between the union and the man\nagement.\nBritain Believed Ready\nto Pay \u2018Token\u2019 to U. S.\nBy United Press\nLONDON, Nov. 22\u2014he British Gov\nernment is considering resuming \u201cto\nken\" payments on its $994,486,367.03\nwar debt to the United States, it\nwas reported today.\nThe reports said that there had\nbeen strong pressure from influen\ntial financial and big business in\nterests in London as well as various\nparliamentary groups.\nIt was suggested that the British\nambassador to Washington, Sir Ron\nald Lindsay, may inform the U. S.\nGovernment that the payments will\nbe started when the United States\npresents its usual semi-annual \u201cre\nminder\" Dec. 15. Britain will get a\nbill then for $122,670,765.05.\n26 Again\nA low of 26 degrees was forecast\nagain for Washington tonight. The\nweather man foresees continued fair\nweather, however, which may be some\nhelp. Low in the last 24 hours was\n27 at 6 a. m. today.\nHoward Coffin Killed!\nin Sea Island Home\nBy United Press\nBRUNSWICK, Ga., Nov. 22\u2014A coroner\u2019s jury will\ndecide, probably today, the circumstances leading up\nto the mysterious and violent death of Howard Earl\nCoffin, nationally known industrialist and intimate\nfriend of Presidents Coolidge and Hoover.\nwaaeE\nCoffin was found shot to death ini\nhis apartment in one of the several\nhundred winter homes of northern\nmillionaires of Sea Island in Bruns\nwick Bay yesterday morning. A single\nshot from a hunting rifle had pene\ntrated his brain. The rifle was be\nside him.\nNO ONE HEARD SHOT\nServants said Coffin had break\nfasted a short while before his body\nwas discovered. He had eaten heart\nily, appeared in excellent spirits. The\nservants did not hear the shot. The\nfact that it was his hunting rifle I\nwhich ended his life, suggested that I\nhe might have been cleaning it in\n\npreparation for today\u2019s hunt.\nCoffin, 64, married Gladys Baker, a 1\nnewspaperwoman, last June. She left\nNew York immediately and was due\nhere today.\nBORN IN OHIO\nCoffin was best known for his as\nsociations with the automotive and\ntextile industries and was for many\nyears a vice president of the Hudson\nMotor Car Co. He was chairman of\nthe Southeastern Cottons, Inc., chair\nman of the Sea Island Development\nCo., chairman of the Young Manage\nment Corporation, vice president and\ndirector of the Farm Chemurgic\nCouncil, a director of the National\nAssociation of Manufacturers, and\nchairman of the National Air Trans\nport Co. He was born in West Mil\nGARNER MARKS BIRTHDAY\nBY PRESIDING IN SENATE\nBy United Press\nVice President John Nance Gar\nner celebrated his 69th birthday\ntoday by:\nArriving at his office at 7:45 a.m.\nPresiding over the Senate at\nnoon.\nPlanning to retire at 9 p. m.\u2014\nas usual.\nBusiness Recession\nCuts U. S. Revenue\nBy United Press\nThe business recession showed up\ntoday in the Treasury\u2019s report on in\nternal revenue collections.\nManufacturers! excise tax collec\ntions, regarded as a barometer of\nbusiness conditions, totaled $159,529,\n879 for the first four months of this\nfiscal year, a decline of $362,362 from\nthe same period last year. In the\nfirst three months collections sur\npassed last year.\nTotal internal revenue collections,\nhowever, continued well ahead of last\nyear, aggregating $1,735,012,436, an in\ncrease of $525,770,205.\nSocial Security taxes contributed\nlargely to the increase.\nCollections\nfrom this source amounted to $219,\n464 654, an increase of $219,368,759\nover last year.\nIncome tax collections aggregated\n$613,271,474, an increase of $227,542,\n444.\nLiquor taxes provided $214,\n396,598. a rise of $485,117. Revenue\nfrom the capital stock tax amounted\nto $137,540,298, an increase of $3,797,\n389. while estate taxes brought in\n$124,860,346, an increase of $69,054,445\nHOWARD COFFIN\ns.1\nton, O., Sept. 6, 1873, the descendant\nof a New England family.\nFuneral services will\nbe held\nWednesday and burial will be in the\ncemetery of Christ\u2019s Church on near\nby St. Simon\u2019s Island.\nNegro Unit Granted\nReview in Picketing\nThe Supreme Court today granted\nthe petition of the New Negro Alli\nance Inc. for review of an injunction\nagainst picketing of a chain grocery\nstore\nwhich refused to employe\nNegroes in an alleged Negro neigh\nborhood.\nThe dispute arose when the alliance\nasked the Sanitary Grocery Co. to\nemploy more Negro clerks in their\nstores located in Negro communities,\nthe high court petition said. The pe\ntition alleged the company discharged\nNegroes it was already employing.\nAs a result, one Negro patroled\npeacefully in front of one of the com\npany\u2019s stores for one day with a\nplacard.\nThe D. C. Federal District Court\nissued a permanent injunction, on ap\nplication of the company, prohibiting\nthe alliance or any of its officers\nThe Circuit Court\nfrom picketing.\nI affirmed the injunction, holding that\nthe picketing grew out of a racial dis\npute rather than a labor dispute, and\nso was not covered by the Norris\nLaGuardia Act.\nStocks Sink\n1 NEW YORK, Nov. 22 United\nStates Steel common stock broke to\na new low for the year at 50 off 3\u2018\ntoday, leading the stock market into\nnew low ground for more than 2\ni years. As the session went into aft\nernoon trading the list was down 1\nto 5 points. aMny leaders made new\nlows. Chrysler broke a 4% points to\n535. General Motors lost nearly 2\nBethlehem dropped more\npoints.\nNon-ferrous metals\nthan 2 points.\nweakened. Gold mining issues alone\nresisted the decline.\nP\nDon't Miss This, Boys and Girls..\nOur Special Christmas serial strip will tell how that vil\nlain, Meany Mo, stormed Santa\u2019s castle. Can Sally Sailor\nand her Soldiers save Santa? Follow this thrilling Toy-\nland adventure beginning today.\nMD 2302\nHI THERE I SLPPOSE\nOURE A NEW POLL\nThis TOTSHOP...\nWHAT\u2019S\nname?\nVOUR\nMINES\nSALLY SAILOR!\nTHEY C ALL ME\nMEANY MO\nBut CM no\nNEWCCMIER.\nLOOK AT THESE\nCOBWEBS./\n32-3\n4\n(0\nC)\nZC0a 2 02\n\n6V\nWHAT\u2019S n-E MATTER, PAL?\nYOU SHOULON T BE SO\nGloomy at ths time\nOF YEAR WHY,\nCARISTAAS WILL j\nSOON BE HERE\n-Cle\nOONT TALK TO\nME ABOUT\nCHRISTMAS.\n6\ny\nO o\n0\nA\n\nTV BEEN ON THIS SHELF\nFOP, FOUR YEARS.\u201d\npO WA*T AC f\nNOBOOY WANTS ME\nNOBODY EVER WROTE\nTO SANTA CLAUS FOR\nMAE.\nWHY SHOULD I BE\nHAPPY f","height":"21068","width":"14196"}}
